      <hedline>
        <hl1>Beauty and the Concorde</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Bernard Raab, aerospace expert, says reverence for beauty may have driven Concorde's creators to select a design that jeopardizes safety (July 31 Herbert Muschamp Critic's Notebook)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Fusing Beauty and Terror, Reverence and Desecration,'' by Herbert Muschamp (Critic's Notebook, July 31):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Fusing Beauty and Terror, Reverence and Desecration,'' by Herbert Muschamp (Critic's Notebook, July 31):</p>
        <p>Yes, the Concorde is beautiful. But it appears possible that a reverence for beauty might have driven the Concorde's creators to select a design that jeopardizes safety.</p>
        <p>The sleek but fixed swept-back delta wing presupposes high takeoff and landing speeds, which put extra stress and heat on the tires. The alternative design, which was favored by Boeing, involves the use of a movable wing that extends at low altitudes, thus allowing lower takeoff and landing speeds, and sweeps back for supersonic cruise at high altitudes.</p>
        <p>Admittedly, this aircraft would not be as pretty a sight at low altitudes, but might have avoided the recent tragedy.</p>
        <p>BERNARD RAAB  Fort Lee, N.J., July 31, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a retired aerospace consultant.</p>
      </block>
